Visualisations of YouTube Ads: Ratings, Relevance, and Viewer Actions

Ad Ratings and Actions Taken with Time Information

Bar plot of Ad Ratings by Action Taken
## Figure 1: A bar chart comparing how users rated ads based on whether they took action. The chart indicates that positive ratings are more common among users who took action (7 users), while negative ratings are more frequent among those who did nothing (16 users). Data was collected over 5 days, from May 08 to May 13.

Number of Ads Encountered vs. Rating

Scatter plot of Rating vs Number of Ads
## Figure 2: A scatter plot showing how users rated YouTube ads based on how many they saw, split by whether they took action after viewing the ads. On average, users who took action gave higher ratings (4) and saw slightly fewer ads (1.9). In contrast, those who did nothing gave lower ratings (2) and saw more ads (2). This pattern suggests that ad fatigue may lower ratings, especially for users who don’t engage with ads.

Familiarity with Product and Ad Relevance

Proportional bar chart of Ad Ratings by Familiarity and Relevance
## Figure 3: This chart shows how ad ratings vary based on users' familiarity with the product and whether the ad felt relevant. Among those familiar with the product, positive ratings were more frequent (8), compared to those unfamiliar (1). Similarly, ads that felt personally relevant received more positive ratings (8) than those that didn’t (1).
